# Firestore Optimistic Updates in Redux

## The Timing Trap

Firestore's Web SDK updates its **local cache immediately** when you call `addDoc`/`setDoc`/`updateDoc`. This means `onSnapshot` fires **before** the write Promise resolves:

```
addDoc() called
  → local cache updated → onSnapshot fires → Redux reducer runs   ← optimistic item still "pending"!
  → server write completes
  → addDoc Promise resolves → cleanup dispatched                   ← too late, duplicate already shown
```

❌ **BAD** — relying on post-`await` cleanup to prevent duplicates:
```ts
await addShoppingItem({...});
dispatch(removePendingOptimisticId(optimisticId)); // onSnapshot already fired with duplicate visible
dispatch(removeShoppingItems([optimisticId]));
```

## The Fix: Resolve Optimistically Inside the Merge Reducer

Match incoming Firestore items against pending optimistic items **by content** inside `mergeFromFirestore`. When the subscription fires with the real item, drop the optimistic item atomically in the same reducer call.

✅ **GOOD** — resolve in the merge reducer by matching originalText (or equivalent content field):
```ts
mergeItemsFromFirestore: (state, action) => {
  const firestoreItems = action.payload;

  // Count available Firestore items per content key to enable 1-to-1 matching
  const countByText = new Map<string, number>();
  for (const fi of firestoreItems) {
    countByText.set(fi.originalText, (countByText.get(fi.originalText) ?? 0) + 1);
  }

  const resolvedIds = new Set<string>();
  for (const item of state.items) {
    if (!state.pendingOptimisticIds.includes(item.id)) continue;
    const available = countByText.get(item.originalText) ?? 0;
    if (available > 0) {
      resolvedIds.add(item.id);
      countByText.set(item.originalText, available - 1);
    }
  }

  state.pendingOptimisticIds = state.pendingOptimisticIds.filter((id) => !resolvedIds.has(id));
  const stillPending = state.items.filter((i) => state.pendingOptimisticIds.includes(i.id));
  state.items = [...firestoreItems, ...stillPending];
},
```

The 1-to-1 count map handles two pending items with the same text correctly.

Post-`await` cleanup dispatches can remain as a safety net but will be no-ops for the happy path.
